3. And as to the Obligation belonging to each os these processes:

(1) Potition does not oblige him who asks, nor him who is asked. For it is an act of need, not of power; the effect does not depend upon the agent, the asker, and therefore cannot induce Obligation.

(2) Promise obliges the promiser, but not the promise-e. For each man in so far as he is a free agent, and (1 Cor. vii. 37) hath power over his own will, may,r exercise that power over himself 3 but has no such power over another.

(3) Commomd obliges not the commander, but obliges the per- son commanded, if there be authority to command: for to command . is the special and appropriate act of authority over another. Thus a Father commands a son 3 a Master, a servant3 a General, his sol- diers3 a King, his people3 and God commands men3 each, as a Superior, commands with authority what is to be done; and by com- manding, imposes an Obligation to do the thing so commanded.
